  "hash": "sha256:3a7f2c19e084b56d1e9a0c3f7b2d5e8a1c4f6b9d2e5a8c1f4b7d0e3a6c9f2b5d",
  "signature": "ed25519:9c2a5f1b8e3d6a0c4f7b2e5d8a1c4f7b0e3d6a9c2f5b8e1d4a7c0f3b6e9d2a5",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Version-controlled solver with documented QA plan, regression test suite, and audit trail for all simulation runs submitted for regulatory review.",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver (STAR-CCM+ v18.02) is maintained under ISO 9001-certified QA procedures. A full regression test suite covering 47 benchmark cases was executed prior to the hemolysis campaign. All simulation runs are logged in an immutable audit trail with hash-verified input decks. QA documentation package submitted to FDA under Q-submission. Requirement met at Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Method of manufactured solutions (MMS) or equivalent demonstrated for the governing equations relevant to hemolysis prediction, including scalar transport.",
      "rationale": "MMS verification was performed for the incompressible Navier-Stokes solver and the passive scalar transport equation used to propagate the hemolysis power-law model. Observed convergence rates match theoretical expectations (second-order spatial, first-order temporal) across three refinement levels. Code verification is satisfied at Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Richardson extrapolation-based GCI reported for all QoIs; discretization uncertainty incorporated into total uncertainty budget.",
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study performed on the FDA centrifugal pump geometry. Grid Convergence Index (GCI) computed per ASME V&V 20 for pressure rise, flow-weighted shear stress, and hemolysis index. Maximum GCI across operating points is 4.1% for hemolysis index. Discretization uncertainty is propagated into the Monte Carlo UQ budget. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions (fluid properties, rotational speed, flow rate, temperature) documented with uncertainty bounds and traceable to calibrated instrumentation.",
      "rationale": "All bench experiments used porcine blood with hematocrit 33±2%, temperature 37±0.5°C, and rotational speeds verified against NIST-traceable tachometer. Flow rates measured with Coriolis flowmeter (±0.5% FS). Test condition uncertainties are propagated into the simulation boundary conditions for the Monte Carlo sweep. Gradation 3 satisfied."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative validation metric (e.g., E%, validation uncertainty interval) computed for hemolysis index at all operating points; comparison includes experimental uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "Normalized error E% computed for hemolysis index at all 5 operating points. Mean E% = 18.3% with maximum 27.1% at the highest speed-flow combination. Validation uncertainty interval computed per ASME V&V 20 and overlaps experimental measurement uncertainty at 4 of 5 points. The single outlier point is attributed to cavitation inception not captured by the deterministic model; sensitivity analysis confirms it does not affect the clinical threshold conclusion. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Hemolysis index predicted by the model is directly linked to the clinical QoI (plasma free hemoglobin or normalized index of hemolysis) used in the regulatory submission.",
      "rationale": "The model outputs normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) via the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law integrated over Lagrangian particle paths. NIH is the same metric reported in the clinical literature and used in the FDA guidance for hemolysis evaluation. A sensitivity analysis confirms the power-law exponents are the dominant uncertainty contributors, and these are swept in the Monte Carlo UQ. Direct traceability from simulation QoI to regulatory QoI is established. Gradation 3 met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments were conducted on the same device geometry, at overlapping operating conditions, and with the same hemolysis measurement protocol as the COU.",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments used the FDA benchmark centrifugal pump geometry (identical to COU geometry). Operating conditions span the clinical envelope (3–6 L/min, 2500–4500 RPM) with 3 of 5 COU points directly matched. Hemolysis measurement protocol (plasma free hemoglobin via spectrophotometry) is identical. Geometric and operating condition relevance is high. Gradation 3 satisfied."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence demonstrated to at least 4 orders of magnitude residual reduction; round-off error assessed and confirmed negligible relative to discretization error.",
      "rationale": "All simulations converged to 5 orders of magnitude reduction in mass and momentum residuals. Double-precision arithmetic used throughout. Round-off error estimated at machine epsilon level, negligible relative to GCI. Gradation 2 achieved; requirement is Gradation 2 at MRL 5 for this factor."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation inputs, boundary conditions, and post-processing scripts independently reviewed by a second analyst; discrepancies documented and resolved.",
      "rationale": "All input decks, boundary condition assignments, and post-processing scripts were independently reviewed by a second CFD engineer not involved in the original setup. Three minor discrepancies (turbulence intensity specification, reference pressure location, particle injection density) were identified and corrected prior to final runs. Review records archived in the project QMS. Gradation 2 met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The mathematical model form — including turbulence closure, hemolysis constitutive law, and blood rheology — is justified by comparison to higher-fidelity models or experimental data across the operating envelope, with documented uncertainty in model-form assumptions.",
      "rationale": "The SST k-ω turbulence closure was selected based on extensive prior use in rotary blood pump simulations reported in the peer-reviewed literature (Bludszuweit 1995; Giersiepen et al. 1990; Taskin et al. 2012) and on the team's own experience across four previous centrifugal pump submissions accepted by FDA. The Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model, while acknowledged to have known scatter at high-shear transient exposures, is the de facto standard for regulatory submissions in this device class and has been accepted in at least six prior 510(k) clearances reviewed by the team's regulatory consultant. An expert panel of three independent biofluid mechanics specialists reviewed the model form selection and unanimously agreed that the chosen approach represents current best practice for Class III VAD submissions at MRL 5. Blood rheology is modeled as a Newtonian fluid at the operating hematocrit, consistent with the majority of published validation studies for this pump geometry. Although a non-Newtonian Carreau-Yasuda model was considered, the difference in predicted NIH at the operating shear rates of interest (predominantly >100 s⁻¹) was estimated at less than 8% based on a sensitivity run at the nominal operating point, which the team judged acceptable given the conservative clinical threshold margin. The Monte Carlo UQ sweep propagates ±20% uncertainty on the power-law coefficients, which the team considers sufficient to bound model-form uncertainty in practice. On balance, the accumulated evidence from prior regulatory experience, expert consensus, and sensitivity analysis provides strong indirect support for the adequacy of the model form, and the team is confident the model is fit for the intended regulatory purpose.",
      "note": "Formal model-form verification against higher-fidelity LES or DNS data across the full operating envelope has not been completed. The achieved credibility level for this factor is Gradation 2; the required level at MRL 5 is Gradation 3. The gap is acknowledged but judged acceptable by the assessment team based on the indirect evidence described above."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All model inputs (geometry, material properties, boundary conditions) are characterized with uncertainty bounds and their influence on hemolysis QoI assessed via sensitivity analysis.",
      "rationale": "Geometry was reconstructed from CMM measurements with ±0.05 mm tolerance; wall roughness characterized by profilometry. Blood viscosity and density assigned from literature with ±5% uncertainty. All boundary condition uncertainties propagated through Monte Carlo UQ (N=500 Latin hypercube samples). Sobol sensitivity indices computed; power-law exponents and impeller tip clearance are the dominant contributors (combined 71% of output variance). Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Blood samples used in hemolysis experiments are characterized for hematocrit, age, and donor variability; inter-sample variability is quantified and reported.",
      "rationale": "Porcine blood from three separate donor pools was used. Hematocrit adjusted to 33±2% for all experiments. Sample age at time of test was ≤24 hours post-collection. Inter-pool variability in baseline plasma free hemoglobin was <5%. Donor variability is documented in the test report. Gradation 2 met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation boundary conditions are demonstrably equivalent to experimental conditions within documented tolerances; any discrepancies are assessed for impact on QoI.",
      "rationale": "Simulation inlet flow rates and rotational speeds were set to match measured experimental values within 1% and 0.5% respectively. Outlet pressure boundary condition was derived from measured pump head curves. Fluid temperature matched to within 0.5°C. Residual discrepancies between simulation inputs and experimental conditions were assessed via a perturbation study; maximum impact on NIH was 2.3%, well within the validation uncertainty budget. Gradation 2 satisfied."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/cou2-vad-acceptance-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-lead",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "Following review of all 13 credibility factors assessed under ASME V&V 40 at Model Risk Level 5, the credibility assessment team concludes that the CFD hemolysis model is accepted for use in the COU as defined. Twelve of thirteen factors meet or exceed their required credibility levels. The single exception — Model Form (achievedLevel 2, requiredLevel 3) — was extensively deliberated. The team notes that the SST k-ω closure and Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law combination represents the regulatory standard of practice for this device class, has been accepted by FDA in multiple prior submissions, and was endorsed unanimously by an independent expert panel. The Monte Carlo UQ sweep with ±20% coefficient uncertainty is judged to bound the model-form gap in a practical sense. The clinical threshold margin (predicted NIH is 38% below the acceptance threshold at the 95th percentile of the UQ distribution) provides additional confidence that the model-form shortfall does not affect the regulatory conclusion. On this basis, and consistent with the team's professional judgment and prior regulatory experience, the overall credibility assessment outcome is Accepted. The model form gap is documented as a finding for future model improvement but does not preclude use of the model for this COU at this time.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
